Product Segmentation Analysis: KVI/SD/PG Classification

Assignment Overview

Objective: Classify 10,299 retail products into three strategic segments based on limited labeled data (54 samples).

Business Context

  • KVI (Key Value Items): Price-competitive essentials that drive store traffic. Customers benchmark prices on these products when choosing retailers.
  • Sales Drivers (SD): High-volume products with moderate profitability. Used to increase transaction volume and attract customers.
  • Profit Generators (PG): High-margin items that contribute disproportionately to bottom line despite lower sales volume.

Challenge

Semi-supervised learning problem:

  • 10,299 total products
  • 54 labeled samples (~0.5%)
  • 10,245 unlabeled samples requiring classification

2.1.1 Section summary

Data quality violations detected across multiple features, compromising model validity and requiring preprocessing decisions.

Theoretical violations:

  • price_elasticity > 0: 87 observations (max: 0.87). Violates law of demand. Indicates Giffen goods, data error, or misspecified elasticity calculation.

Logical impossibilities:

  • total_units_sold < 0: Negative quantities (min: -10.56). Represents returns dominating sales or erroneous aggregation.
  • total_revenue < 0: Min -197.98. Net-negative transactions shouldn't exist in sales data.

Type inconsistencies:

  • total_units_sold is float (mean: 233.91). Should be integer. Suggests weighted averaging, prorated periods, or fractional unit handling that wasn't discretized.

Implications for pipeline:

  • Feature engineering validity compromised (revenue_per_unit division by negative/zero).
  • Model will learn spurious patterns from measurement artifacts.
  • Semi-supervised propagation will spread label noise if outliers exist in unlabeled set.

Preprocessing options:

  • Aggressive filtering: Remove positive elasticity rows, negatives revenues. Loss ~1% of data.
  • Imputation strategy: Cap elasticity at 0, treat negatives as return-heavy class, round total_units_sold after validating aggregation logic.

Decisions for further analysis:

  • Filtering of invalid rows
  • Transformation of the total_units_sold to integer dtype
  • Outliers detection (both univariate and multivariate)
  • Possibility of Z-Score scaling of the features
  • Feature engineering on clean and analsyis-ready data, before scaling

2.2 Filtering and cleaning the data, feature engineering and outliers detection

Feature engineering must occur after cleaning but before outlier detection to avoid propagating errors while enabling univariate and multivariate anomaly identification.

Sequence rationale:

  1. Cleaning first:

    • Remove structural errors (negative units, impossible values, duplicates).
    • Prevents engineered features from inheriting invalid base values.
    • Example: revenue_per_unit = total_revenue / total_units_sold becomes undefined with negative denominators.

  2. Feature engineering second:

    • Creates derived metrics that expose multivariate relationships.
    • Example: conversion_rate = total_units_sold / total_online_views reveals behavioral anomalies invisible in raw features.
    • Interaction terms amplify outlier signatures (e.g., high elasticity low revenue contradicts economics).

  3. Outlier detection last:

    • Univariate methods on raw features miss relationship-based anomalies.
    • Engineered features make business-logic violations detectable (e.g., profit_margin_proxy < 0 when both inputs are positive).
    • Isolation Forest/Mahalanobis distance work on full feature spaceneeds complete set including derived metrics.

Why not reverse order:

  • Detecting outliers on raw features alone: Misses products with valid individual values but impossible combinations.
  • Engineering after outlier removal: Loses informationsome products only become anomalous when interactions are computed.

Pipeline: Clean Engineer Detect Remove/Flag Model.

2.2.1 Features engineering

Engineered features target economic relationships, behavioral signals, and competitive positioning that raw metrics don't capture.

Ratio-based features (margin and efficiency):

  • revenue_per_unit = total_revenue / total_units_sold unit price proxy, margin indicator.
  • conversion_rate = total_units_sold / total_online_views demand efficiency, purchase intent.
  • basket_value_ratio = mean_added_revenue_to_basket / total_revenue basket influence strength relative to total sales.
  • profit_margin_proxy = mean_basket_profit / mean_added_revenue_to_basket profitability per basket addition.

Competitive pressure metrics:

  • competitive_pressure = competitive_price_range / revenue_per_unit normalized competition intensity (range relative to product's price level).
  • price_stability = 1 / (price_volatility + 0.001) inverse volatility, rewards stable pricing.

Behavioral interaction terms:

  • sales_velocity = (total_units_sold / total_online_views) * median_basket_position conversion rate weighted by purchase timing.
  • elasticity_revenue_interaction = price_elasticity * total_revenue responsiveness scaled by sales magnitude.
  • volatility_competition_interaction = price_volatility * competitive_price_range pricing instability under competitive pressure.

Positional features:

  • early_basket_indicator = 1 if median_basket_position <= 2 else 0 binary flag for impulse/staple items.
  • basket_profit_lift = mean_basket_profit - (total_revenue / total_units_sold) incremental basket profitability beyond product's own margin.

Expected segment signatures:

  • KVI: High price_elasticity (negative), high competitive_pressure, low median_basket_position, low conversion_rate.
  • SD: High total_units_sold, high conversion_rate, moderate revenue_per_unit, low profit_margin_proxy.
  • PG: High revenue_per_unit, high profit_margin_proxy, low price_elasticity (inelastic), low sales_velocity, low competitive_pressure.

Division safety: Add epsilon (1e-6) to denominators to handle zero/near-zero values.

# IQR-based outlier detection
def detect_outliers_iqr(data, feature):
    Q1 = data[feature].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = data[feature].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower_bound = Q1 - 3.5 * IQR
    upper_bound = Q3 + 3.5 * IQR
    outliers = ((data[feature] < lower_bound) | (data[feature] > upper_bound))
    return outliers, lower_bound, upper_bound

# Detect outliers for each feature
outlier_summary = []
for feature in numeric_features:
    outliers, lower, upper = detect_outliers_iqr(df_engineered, feature)
    n_outliers = outliers.sum()
    pct_outliers = (n_outliers / len(df)) * 100

    outlier_summary.append({
        'feature': feature,
        'n_outliers': n_outliers,
        'pct_outliers': pct_outliers,
        'lower_bound': lower,
        'upper_bound': upper
    })

outlier_df = pd.DataFrame(outlier_summary).sort_values('pct_outliers', ascending=False)
print("\nUnivariate Outliers Summary:")
display(outlier_df)

2.2.2 Multivariate Outliers (Isolation Forest)

Isolation Forest and multivariate outlier detection prevent model degradation by identifying anomalous patterns that univariate methods miss.

Isolation Forest advantages:

  • Detects anomalies in high-dimensional feature space without distance metrics.
  • Computationally efficient (O(n log n)) compared to density-based methods.
  • No assumption of data distribution (non-parametric).
  • Isolates outliers by random partitioninganomalies require fewer splits to separate.

Multivariate outlier analysis necessity:

  • Univariate checks (z-score, IQR per feature) miss interaction effects.
  • Point may be normal in each dimension but anomalous in combination (e.g., high elasticity + low revenue contradicts economics).
  • Mahalanobis distance captures correlated feature space geometry.

Impact on modeling:

  • Prevents outliers from dominating loss function (especially in gradient-based methods).
  • Reduces variance in cross-validation performance.
  • Improves semi-supervised learning qualityoutliers distort similarity graphs in label propagation.
  • Enhances interpretabilitySHAP values reflect true patterns, not artifacts.

Application to this dataset:

  • Identify products with contradictory metrics (positive elasticity + high sales).
  • Flag measurement errors vs. genuine edge cases (returns, data collection issues).
  • Clean training set before propagating pseudo-labels to 10,245 unlabeled samples.

from sklearn.ensemble import IsolationForest
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

# Prepare data for multivariate outlier detection
df_numeric = df_engineered[numeric_features].copy()



# Scale features
scaler = StandardScaler()
df_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(df_numeric)

# Isolation Forest
iso_forest = IsolationForest(
    contamination=0.05,  # Expect 5% outliers
    random_state=SEED,
    n_jobs=-1
)

# Predict outliers (-1 for outliers, 1 for inliers)
outlier_labels = iso_forest.fit_predict(df_scaled)
df_numeric['is_outlier_multivariate'] = (outlier_labels == -1)

print(f"\nMultivariate outliers detected: {df_numeric['is_outlier_multivariate'].sum()} ({df_numeric['is_outlier_multivariate'].mean()*100:.2f}%)")

Distinction:

Univariate outliers:

  • Single feature takes extreme value while others remain plausible.
  • Example: Product with profit_margin_proxy = 8.5 (upper outlier) but normal revenue_per_unit, total_units_sold.
  • Interpretation: Genuinely high-margin productexactly what defines PG segment.
  • Business reality: Market naturally contains low-volume/high-margin and high-volume/low-margin products.

Multivariate outliers:

  • Feature combination violates economic logic or relationship constraints.
  • Example: High conversion_rate (0.8) + negative total_revenue + high price_elasticity (positive).
  • Interpretation: Measurement error, data corruption, or edge case (returns, samples, bundles) that doesn't represent product economics.
  • No valid business scenario produces this combination.

Univariate outlier retention rationale:

  • profit_margin_proxy (4.7% outliers): High/low margin products are real segment differentiators, not errors. PG class likely concentrates here.
  • basket_value_ratio (3.9% outliers): Products with disproportionate basket influence are strategically importantremoving them loses KVI/SD signal.
  • sales_velocity (1.4% outliers): Extremes capture impulse items (high) vs. researched purchases (low)critical for classification.
  • Engineered features may amplify legitimate variance that distinguishes KVI/SD/PG segments.

2.3.2 Features scaling

Scaling before clustering is necessary because distance-based algorithms weight features by their absolute magnitude, not their informative value.

Without scaling:

  • total_revenue (range: -197 to 73600) dominates distance calculations over price_elasticity (range: -3.3 to 0.87).
  • Euclidean distance becomes sqrt((revenue)^2 + (elasticity)^2) where revenue term is 10,000x larger.
  • Clustering groups products by revenue similarity onlyignores elasticity, volatility, competitive pressure entirely.
  • K-means centroids drift toward high-variance features, creating revenue-stratified clusters instead of behavior-based segments.

With scaling (RobustScaler):

  • All features contribute proportionally to distance metric.
  • Products cluster by multivariate similarity across pricing behavior, profitability, demand responsiveness.
  • Enables detection of patterns like "low revenue + high margin + low elasticity" = PG candidate.

3.1.1 Decision Tree estimation on the labeled data

Rationale

Even though the labeled data are on a tiny part of the data. Simple decision tree, based on low number of features and with limited depth may produce singificant insight into the groups classification.

Cons

The labeled data may not be (and most likely are not) proper representation of the total population, which may provide us with misleading information about the groups classification.

How to approach

DT needs to remain simple, with few decision rules. When applied to the unlabeled data, the predicted groups must follow the overall expected economic logic behind the predicted groups.

In[25]:

# Extract decision rules
print("\n" + "="*80)
print("DECISION RULES AND THRESHOLD VALUES")
print("="*80 + "\n")

tree = dt.tree_

def get_rules(tree, feature_names, node=0, depth=0, rule=""):
    """Extract decision rules from tree"""
    indent = "  " * depth

    if tree.feature[node] != -2:  # Not a leaf
        name = feature_names[tree.feature[node]]
        thr = tree.threshold[node]

        print(f"{indent}Node {node}: Split on '{name}' <= {thr:.4f}")
        print(f"{indent}  Samples: {tree.n_node_samples[node]}, Impurity: {tree.impurity[node]:.4f}")

        # Left branch
        print(f"{indent}   LEFT ( {thr:.4f}):")
        get_rules(tree, feature_names, tree.children_left[node], depth+1,
                  rule + f" AND {name} <= {thr:.4f}")

        # Right branch
        print(f"{indent}   RIGHT (> {thr:.4f}):")
        get_rules(tree, feature_names, tree.children_right[node], depth+1,
                  rule + f" AND {name} > {thr:.4f}")
    else:  # Leaf node
        class_counts = tree.value[node][0]
        predicted_class = np.argmax(class_counts)
        class_names = ['KVI', 'PG', 'SD']

        print(f"{indent}LEAF {node}: Predict {class_names[predicted_class]}")
        print(f"{indent}  Class distribution: KVI={int(class_counts[0])}, "
              f"PG={int(class_counts[1])}, SD={int(class_counts[2])}")
        print(f"{indent}  Rule: {rule}\n")

get_rules(tree,  numeric_features)
# Select top 3-4 features for clustering
dt_selected_features = top_features_dt[:4]  # Take top 4

Target segment characteristics:

  • Cluster 0 (KVI): High views, High competition pressure, Med profit, Low velocity
  • Cluster 1 (SD): Med - Low views, Med competition pressure, Low profit, Med velocity
  • Cluster 2 (PG): Med views, Low competition pressure, High profit, High velocity

In this part of the modelling, we are not yet enforcing the expected groups distribution accros the data population.

class MultiFeatureMonotonicKMeans:
    """K-Means with multiple monotonicity constraints"""

    def __init__(self, n_clusters=3, feature_constraints=None, constraint_weights=None,
                 random_state=42, max_iter=300, n_init=20):
        """
        Parameters:
        -----------
        feature_constraints : dict
            {feature_idx: 'ascending' or 'descending'}
            Example: {0: 'descending', 1: 'ascending', 2: 'descending'}
        constraint_weights : dict or None
            {feature_idx: weight} - importance of each constraint
            If None, all features weighted equally
        """
        self.n_clusters = n_clusters
        self.feature_constraints = feature_constraints or {}
        self.constraint_weights = constraint_weights or {k: 1.0 for k in feature_constraints.keys()}
        self.random_state = random_state
        self.max_iter = max_iter
        self.n_init = n_init
        self.kmeans = None
        self.cluster_mapping = None
        self.violation_score = None

    def fit(self, X, feature_names=None):
        """Fit K-Means and find optimal cluster ordering"""
        self.feature_names = feature_names

        # Standard K-Means
        self.kmeans = KMeans(
            n_clusters=self.n_clusters,
            random_state=self.random_state,
            max_iter=self.max_iter,
            n_init=self.n_init
        )
        self.kmeans.fit(X)

        # Find best cluster ordering
        centroids = self.kmeans.cluster_centers_
        self.cluster_mapping, self.violation_score = self._find_best_ordering(centroids)

        return self

    def _find_best_ordering(self, centroids):
        """
        Try all permutations of cluster orderings and find the one
        that best satisfies monotonicity constraints
        """
        from itertools import permutations

        n = self.n_clusters
        all_permutations = list(permutations(range(n)))

        best_mapping = None
        best_score = float('inf')

        for perm in all_permutations:
            # Create mapping: old_id -> new_id
            mapping = {perm[i]: i for i in range(n)}

            # Compute violation score
            score = self._compute_violation_score(centroids, mapping)

            if score < best_score:
                best_score = score
                best_mapping = mapping

        return best_mapping, best_score

    def _compute_violation_score(self, centroids, mapping):
        """
        Compute how much the ordering violates monotonicity constraints
        Lower score = better (0 = perfect monotonicity)
        """
        # Reorder centroids according to mapping
        reordered_centroids = np.zeros_like(centroids)
        for old_id, new_id in mapping.items():
            reordered_centroids[new_id] = centroids[old_id]

        total_violation = 0.0

        for feature_idx, constraint in self.feature_constraints.items():
            weight = self.constraint_weights[feature_idx]
            feature_values = reordered_centroids[:, feature_idx]

            # Check monotonicity violations
            if constraint == 'ascending':
                # Should be: cluster_0 < cluster_1 < cluster_2
                for i in range(self.n_clusters - 1):
                    if feature_values[i] > feature_values[i + 1]:
                        # Violation: should increase but decreases
                        violation = (feature_values[i] - feature_values[i + 1])
                        total_violation += weight * violation

            elif constraint == 'descending':
                # Should be: cluster_0 > cluster_1 > cluster_2
                for i in range(self.n_clusters - 1):
                    if feature_values[i] < feature_values[i + 1]:
                        # Violation: should decrease but increases
                        violation = (feature_values[i + 1] - feature_values[i])
                        total_violation += weight * violation

        return total_violation

    def predict(self, X):
        """Predict cluster labels with monotonic ordering"""
        original_labels = self.kmeans.predict(X)
        remapped_labels = np.array([self.cluster_mapping[label] for label in original_labels])
        return remapped_labels

    @property
    def labels_(self):
        """Get training labels with monotonic ordering"""
        original_labels = self.kmeans.labels_
        return np.array([self.cluster_mapping[label] for label in original_labels])

    def print_cluster_ordering(self, X, original_feature_names):
        """Print resulting cluster means and check monotonicity"""
        remapped_labels = self.labels_

        print("\n" + "="*80)
        print("CLUSTER ORDERING VALIDATION")
        print("="*80 + "\n")

        print("Target constraints:")
        for feat_idx, constraint in self.feature_constraints.items():
            feat_name = original_feature_names[feat_idx]
            print(f"  {feat_name}: {constraint.upper()}")

        print(f"\nCluster mapping (original -> new): {self.cluster_mapping}")
        print(f"Violation score: {self.violation_score:.6f} (0 = perfect)")

        print("\nCluster means (reordered):")
        for cluster_id in range(self.n_clusters):
            cluster_data = X[remapped_labels == cluster_id]
            print(f"\n  Cluster {cluster_id}: {len(cluster_data)} samples")
            for feat_idx in self.feature_constraints.keys():
                feat_name = original_feature_names[feat_idx]
                mean_val = cluster_data[:, feat_idx].mean()
                print(f"    {feat_name}: {mean_val:.4f}")

        # Check if monotonicity is satisfied
        print("\nMonotonicity check:")
        for feat_idx, constraint in self.feature_constraints.items():
            feat_name = original_feature_names[feat_idx]
            values = []
            for cluster_id in range(self.n_clusters):
                cluster_data = X[remapped_labels == cluster_id]
                values.append(cluster_data[:, feat_idx].mean())

            if constraint == 'ascending':
                is_monotonic = all(values[i] <= values[i+1] for i in range(len(values)-1))
                direction = ""
            else:
                is_monotonic = all(values[i] >= values[i+1] for i in range(len(values)-1))
                direction = ""

            status = "" if is_monotonic else ""
            print(f"  {status} {feat_name} {direction}: {'  '.join([f'{v:.3f}' for v in values])}")

3.1.3 Chapter summary

Findings Decition tree model provides reasonable and logical prediction and groups characteristic for unlabeled part of the portfolio.

The DT predicted groups follow the expected definitions related to the product groups (KVI - Highest views, and competitive pressure, PG - lowest competitive pressure, highest mean basket profit, SD - lowest views, mid competitive pressure)

Clustering algoirthm provides reasonable cluster specifications, keeping same monotonicities as the DT. When applied to labeled data, the clustering algorithm accuracy and confusion matrix show mixed results, misclassifying almost entirely SD group of products.

Conclusion Neither of the models can be used solely for the final class prediction, DT lacks more robust estimation data base, clustering algoirthm shows singificant error rate for SD product group.

3.2 Hyperparameter Tuning - Non Constraint clustering

In this section, we are not going to impose any constraints on the clustering algorithm, neither the distribution properties, nor the monotonicities.

We are looking for the best clustering algorithm (given the algorithm type, estimation method, other hyperparameters) which will separate the data into three distinctive groups.

def create_cluster_mapping_by_pressure(df_train, cluster_labels, df_test, test_cluster_labels, y_test):
    """
    Create cluster-to-segment mapping ensuring all 3 segments assigned based on competitive_pressure

    Parameters:
    -----------
    df_train : DataFrame
        Training data with features
    cluster_labels : array
        Cluster assignments for training data
    df_test : DataFrame
        Test data (for validation)
    test_cluster_labels : array
        Cluster assignments for test data
    y_test : Series
        True labels for test data

    Returns:
    --------
    cluster_mapping : dict
        Mapping from cluster_id to segment based on competitive_pressure
    """

    # Calculate mean competitive_pressure for each cluster on training data
    cluster_pressure_means = {}
    for cluster_id in range(3):
        cluster_data = df_train.loc[df_train.index[cluster_labels == cluster_id]]
        cluster_pressure_means[cluster_id] = cluster_data['competitive_pressure'].mean()

    # Sort clusters by competitive_pressure (descending: HIGH -> MED -> LOW)
    sorted_clusters = sorted(cluster_pressure_means.items(), key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)

    # Assign segments: Highest pressure = KVI, Medium = SD, Lowest = PG
    cluster_mapping = {
        sorted_clusters[0][0]: 'KVI',  # Highest pressure
        sorted_clusters[1][0]: 'SD',   # Medium pressure
        sorted_clusters[2][0]: 'PG'    # Lowest pressure
    }

    print("Cluster mapping based on competitive_pressure (training data):")
    print(f"{'Cluster':<10} {'Mean Pressure':<18} {'Assigned Segment':<10}")
    print("-" * 45)
    for cluster_id, segment in cluster_mapping.items():
        pressure = cluster_pressure_means[cluster_id]
        print(f"{cluster_id:<10} {pressure:<18.4f} {segment:<10}")

    # Validate mapping on test set
    if df_test is not None and test_cluster_labels is not None and y_test is not None:
        print("\nValidation on test set:")
        df_test_temp = pd.DataFrame({
            'true_label': y_test.values,
            'cluster': test_cluster_labels,
            'predicted': [cluster_mapping[c] for c in test_cluster_labels]
        })

        # Show distribution
        print("\nTest set cluster distribution:")
        for cluster_id in range(3):
            count = (df_test_temp['cluster'] == cluster_id).sum()
            segment = cluster_mapping[cluster_id]
            print(f"  Cluster {cluster_id}  {segment}: {count} samples")

        # Calculate accuracy
        accuracy = (df_test_temp['true_label'] == df_test_temp['predicted']).mean()
        print(f"\nTest accuracy with pressure-based mapping: {accuracy:.4f}")

    return cluster_mapping

from sklearn.model_selection import ParameterGrid

print("="*80)
print("K-MEANS HYPERPARAMETER OPTIMIZATION")
print("="*80 + "\n")

# Define parameter grid
kmeans_param_grid = {
    'n_init': [10, 20, 50],
    'max_iter': [300, 500, 1000],
    'algorithm': ['lloyd', 'elkan']
}

print(f"Testing {len(list(ParameterGrid(kmeans_param_grid)))} configurations...\n")

kmeans_results = []

for params in ParameterGrid(kmeans_param_grid):
    # Train on unlabeled data
    kmeans_model = KMeans(
        n_clusters=3,
        random_state=SEED,
        **params
    )
    kmeans_model.fit(X_train_dt)

    # Training metrics
    train_labels = kmeans_model.labels_
    train_silhouette = silhouette_score(X_train_dt, train_labels)
    train_db = davies_bouldin_score(X_train_dt, train_labels)

    # Test predictions
    test_labels = kmeans_model.predict(X_test_dt)

    # Map to segments
    df_test_temp = pd.DataFrame({
        'true_label': y_test.values,
        'cluster': test_labels
    })

    cluster_mapping = {}
    for cluster_id in range(3):
        cluster_samples = df_test_temp[df_test_temp['cluster'] == cluster_id]
        if len(cluster_samples) > 0:
            cluster_mapping[cluster_id] = cluster_samples['true_label'].mode()[0]
        else:
            cluster_mapping[cluster_id] = 'UNKNOWN'

    df_test_temp['predicted'] = df_test_temp['cluster'].map(cluster_mapping)
    test_accuracy = (df_test_temp['true_label'] == df_test_temp['predicted']).mean()
    test_ari = adjusted_rand_score(df_test_temp['true_label'], df_test_temp['cluster'])



    kmeans_results.append({
        'params': params,
        'train_silhouette': train_silhouette,
        'train_db': train_db,
        'test_accuracy': test_accuracy,
        'test_ari': test_ari,
        'model': kmeans_model,
        'cluster_mapping': cluster_mapping,
        'train_labels': train_labels,
        'test_labels': test_labels
    })


# After K-Means hyperparameter optimization, before storing results:
for result in kmeans_results:
    # Replace existing mapping with pressure-based

# Define parameter grid
gmm_param_grid = {
    'covariance_type': ['full', 'tied', 'diag', 'spherical'],
    'n_init': [10, 20, 50],
    'max_iter': [100, 200, 500]
}

print(f"Testing {len(list(ParameterGrid(gmm_param_grid)))} configurations...\n")

gmm_results = []

for params in ParameterGrid(gmm_param_grid):
    # Train on unlabeled data
    gmm_model = GaussianMixture(
        n_components=3,
        random_state=SEED,
        **params
    )
    gmm_model.fit(X_train_dt)

    # Training metrics
    train_labels = gmm_model.predict(X_train_dt)
    train_silhouette = silhouette_score(X_train_dt, train_labels)
    train_db = davies_bouldin_score(X_train_dt, train_labels)

    # Test predictions
    test_labels = gmm_model.predict(X_test_dt)

    # Map to segments
    df_test_temp = pd.DataFrame({
        'true_label': y_test.values,
        'cluster': test_labels
    })

    cluster_mapping = {}
    for cluster_id in range(3):
        cluster_samples = df_test_temp[df_test_temp['cluster'] == cluster_id]
        if len(cluster_samples) > 0:
            cluster_mapping[cluster_id] = cluster_samples['true_label'].mode()[0]
        else:
            cluster_mapping[cluster_id] = 'UNKNOWN'

    df_test_temp['predicted'] = df_test_temp['cluster'].map(cluster_mapping)
    test_accuracy = (df_test_temp['true_label'] == df_test_temp['predicted']).mean()
    test_ari = adjusted_rand_score(df_test_temp['true_label'], df_test_temp['cluster'])

    gmm_results.append({
        'params': params,
        'train_silhouette': train_silhouette,
        'train_db': train_db,
        'test_accuracy': test_accuracy,
        'test_ari': test_ari,
        'model': gmm_model,
        'cluster_mapping': cluster_mapping,
        'train_labels': train_labels,
        'test_labels': test_labels
    })

    )

print("\n" + "="*80)
print("HIERARCHICAL CLUSTERING HYPERPARAMETER OPTIMIZATION")
print("="*80 + "\n")

# Define parameter grid
hierarchical_param_grid = {
    'linkage': ['ward', 'complete', 'average'],
    'metric': ['euclidean']  # Ward only works with euclidean
}

print(f"Testing {len(list(ParameterGrid(hierarchical_param_grid)))} configurations...\n")

hierarchical_results = []

for params in ParameterGrid(hierarchical_param_grid):
    # Skip invalid combinations
    if params['linkage'] == 'ward' and params['metric'] != 'euclidean':
        continue

    # Train on unlabeled data
    hierarchical_model = AgglomerativeClustering(
        n_clusters=3,
        **params
    )
    train_labels = hierarchical_model.fit_predict(X_train_dt)

    # Training metrics
    train_silhouette = silhouette_score(X_train_dt, train_labels)
    train_db = davies_bouldin_score(X_train_dt, train_labels)

    # Test predictions (using KNN since hierarchical has no predict)
    from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=5)
    knn.fit(X_train_dt, train_labels)
    test_labels = knn.predict(X_test_dt)

    # Create pressure-based mapping to ensure all 3 segments assigned
    cluster_mapping = create_cluster_mapping_by_pressure(
        df_train=df_engineered.loc[train_indices],
        cluster_labels=train_labels,
        df_test=None,
        test_cluster_labels=test_labels,
        y_test=None
    )

    # Evaluate on test set
    df_test_temp = pd.DataFrame({
        'true_label': y_test.values,
        'cluster': test_labels,
        'predicted': [cluster_mapping[c] for c in test_labels]
    })

    test_accuracy = (df_test_temp['true_label'] == df_test_temp['predicted']).mean()
    test_ari = adjusted_rand_score(df_test_temp['true_label'], df_test_temp['cluster'])

    hierarchical_results.append({
        'params': params,
        'train_silhouette': train_silhouette,
        'train_db': train_db,
        'test_accuracy': test_accuracy,
        'test_ari': test_ari,
        'model': hierarchical_model,
        'knn_predictor': knn,
        'cluster_mapping': cluster_mapping,
        'train_labels': train_labels,
        'test_labels': test_labels
    })

# Find best model

3.3 Modelling discusion and findings

The hyperoptimized clustering model (GMM picked as the best performed) improves the misclassification, keeping the economic rationale and expected cluster properties. All the three estimated models should be used in a final ensamble model, providing complex and robust product group prediction.

4 Model selection - prior products distribution

Objective: Create ensamble model. Develop redistribution pipeline, where the ensembled model predictions are adjusted by the given product distribution expectation (10% KVI, 30% SD and 60% PD).

4.1 Ensamble framework

Rationale

Decision tree (supervised baseline):

  • Learns explicit rules from 54 labeled samples.
  • Captures known KVI/SD/PG decision boundaries based on ground truth.
  • Interpretable feature splits validate business logic (e.g., "if profit_margin_proxy > 2.5 and price_elasticity < -1.0 PG").
  • Weakness: Overfits small labeled set, the labeled data may not be representative of the whole sample

Constrained clustering (distribution-aware):

  • K-means with k=3 on full 10,299 products.
  • Applies constraints and monotonicities on the selected features
  • Strength: Leverages unlabeled data structure, respects business constraints.
  • Weakness: No ground truth anchorclusters may not align with true labels.

Hyperparameter-optimized clustering (data-driven segmentation):

  • Grid search silhouette score, Davies-Bouldin index on scaled features.
  • Finds natural data partitions without assumptions.
  • Weakness: No guarantee clusters correspond to business definitions.

# Enhanced distribution adjustment function using cluster distances
def adjust_predictions_with_cluster_distances(df, clustering_model, X_scaled, target_distribution,
                                               cluster_mapping, initial_pred_col='initial_prediction',
                                               model_type='gmm'):
    """
    Adjust predictions to match target distribution using cluster distances
    for intelligent reallocation.
    """

    n_samples = len(df)
    target_counts = {seg: int(n_samples * prop) for seg, prop in target_distribution.items()}

    # Adjust for rounding
    diff = n_samples - sum(target_counts.values())
    if diff != 0:
        max_seg = max(target_distribution, key=target_distribution.get)
        target_counts[max_seg] += diff

    print(f"Target distribution ({n_samples} samples):")
    for seg in ['KVI', 'SD', 'PG']:
        count = target_counts[seg]
        print(f"  {seg}: {count:5d} ({count/n_samples*100:5.1f}%)")
    print()

    # Current distribution
    current_counts = df[initial_pred_col].value_counts().to_dict()
    for seg in ['KVI', 'SD', 'PG']:
        if seg not in current_counts:
            current_counts[seg] = 0

    print("Current distribution:")
    for seg in ['KVI', 'SD', 'PG']:
        count = current_counts[seg]
        print(f"  {seg}: {count:5d} ({count/n_samples*100:5.1f}%)")
    print()

    # Get cluster centers and labels based on model type
    if model_type == 'kmeans':
        cluster_centers = clustering_model.cluster_centers_
        cluster_labels = clustering_model.predict(X_scaled)
    elif model_type == 'gmm':
        cluster_centers = clustering_model.means_
        cluster_labels = clustering_model.predict(X_scaled)
    else:  # hierarchical
        # For hierarchical, calculate centroids from assignments
        from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
        knn_temp = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=5)
        knn_temp.fit(X_scaled, clustering_model.labels_)
        cluster_labels = knn_temp.predict(X_scaled)
        cluster_centers = np.array([X_scaled[clustering_model.labels_ == i].mean(axis=0)
                                    for i in range(3)])

    # Create reverse mapping: segment -> cluster_id
    reverse_mapping = {v: k for k, v in cluster_mapping.items()}

    # Calculate distances from each point to all cluster centers
    df_work = df.reset_index(drop=True).copy()
    df_work['cluster_label'] = cluster_labels

    for seg in ['KVI', 'SD', 'PG']:
        cluster_id = reverse_mapping[seg]
        center = cluster_centers[cluster_id]
        # Euclidean distance to cluster center
        distances = np.linalg.norm(X_scaled - center, axis=1)
        df_work[f'dist_to_{seg}'] = distances

    # Calculate surplus and deficit
    surplus = {}
    deficit = {}
    for seg in ['KVI', 'SD', 'PG']:
        diff = current_counts[seg] - target_counts[seg]
        if diff > 0:
            surplus[seg] = diff
        elif diff < 0:
            deficit[seg] = -diff

    print("Adjustments needed:")
    if surplus:
        print("  Surplus (need to remove):")
        for seg, count in surplus.items():
            print(f"    {seg}: {count}")
    if deficit:
        print("  Deficit (need to add):")
        for seg, count in deficit.items():
            print(f"    {seg}: {count}")
    print()

    # Initialize adjusted predictions
    adjusted_predictions = df_work[initial_pred_col].copy()
    reallocation_log = []

    # Reallocate from surplus to deficit segments
    for surplus_seg, surplus_count in surplus.items():
        surplus_mask = (adjusted_predictions == surplus_seg)
        surplus_indices = df_work[surplus_mask].index

        if len(surplus_indices) == 0:
            continue

        candidates = df_work.loc[surplus_indices].copy()

        # Calculate reallocation score: weighted distance to deficit segments
        # Lower distance = higher score (more suitable for reallocation)
        candidates['reallocation_score'] = 0
        for deficit_seg in deficit.keys():
            # Use inverse distance as score (closer = higher score)
            candidates['reallocation_score'] += (1.0 / (candidates[f'dist_to_{deficit_seg}'] + 0.01))

        # Also consider distance from current cluster (further = easier to reallocate)
        candidates['reallocation_score'] += candidates[f'dist_to_{surplus_seg}'] * 0.5

        # Sort by reallocation score (higher = better candidate for reallocation)
        candidates = candidates.sort_values('reallocation_score', ascending=False)

        n_to_reallocate = min(surplus_count, sum(deficit.values()))

        for idx in candidates.index[:n_to_reallocate]:
            # Find best deficit segment (closest cluster)
            best_deficit_seg = None
            best_distance = float('inf')

            for deficit_seg in list(deficit.keys()):
                if deficit[deficit_seg] > 0:
                    dist = df_work.loc[idx, f'dist_to_{deficit_seg}']
                    if dist < best_distance:
                        best_distance = dist
                        best_deficit_seg = deficit_seg

            if best_deficit_seg:
                old_seg = adjusted_predictions.iloc[idx]
                adjusted_predictions.iloc[idx] = best_deficit_seg
                deficit[best_deficit_seg] -= 1

                reallocation_log.append({
                    'product_id': df_work.loc[idx, 'product_id'],
                    'from': old_seg,
                    'to': best_deficit_seg,
                    'distance_to_new': best_distance,
                    'distance_to_old': df_work.loc[idx, f'dist_to_{old_seg}'],
                    'distance_ratio': best_distance / (df_work.loc[idx, f'dist_to_{old_seg}'] + 1e-10),
                    'initial_pred': df_work.loc[idx, initial_pred_col]
                })

                if deficit[best_deficit_seg] == 0:
                    del deficit[best_deficit_seg]

    # Verify final distribution
    final_counts = adjusted_predictions.value_counts().to_dict()
    print("Final distribution after adjustment:")
    for seg in ['KVI', 'SD', 'PG']:
        count = final_counts.get(seg, 0)
        target = target_counts[seg]
        match = "" if count == target else ""
        print(f"  {match} {seg}: {count:5d} (target: {target:5d})")
    print()

    # Statistics on reallocated samples
    if reallocation_log:
        realloc_df = pd.DataFrame(reallocation_log)
        print("Reallocation statistics:")
        print(f"  Mean distance to new cluster: {realloc_df['distance_to_new'].mean():.4f}")
        print(f"  Mean distance to old cluster: {realloc_df['distance_to_old'].mean():.4f}")
        print(f"  Mean distance ratio (new/old): {realloc_df['distance_ratio'].mean():.4f}")
        print(f"  Median distance ratio: {realloc_df['distance_ratio'].median():.4f}")

    reallocation_info = {
        'n_reallocated': len(reallocation_log),
        'reallocation_log': reallocation_log
    }

    print(f"\nTotal samples reallocated: {len(reallocation_log)}")

    return adjusted_predictions, reallocation_info

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np

# Visualization: Segment profiles after reallocation
print("\n" + "="*80)
print("SEGMENT PROFILES AFTER REALLOCATION - ALL 4 FEATURES (KDE + MEANS + QUANTILE LIMITS)")
print("="*80 + "\n")

fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(18, 14))
axes = axes.ravel()

features_viz = ['total_online_views', 'competitive_pressure', 'mean_basket_profit', 'sales_velocity']
colors = {'KVI': 'blue', 'SD': 'green', 'PG': 'red'}

for idx, feature in enumerate(features_viz):
    # Calculate 1st and 99th percentiles for x-axis limits
    q01 = df_train_final_stats[feature].quantile(0.01)
    q99 = df_train_final_stats[feature].quantile(0.99)

    # Plot histograms and KDE for each segment
    for segment in ['KVI', 'SD', 'PG']:
        data = df_train_final_stats[df_train_final_stats['final_prediction'] == segment][feature]

        if len(data) > 1:
            # Filter data within quantile range for visualization
            data_filtered = data[(data >= q01) & (data <= q99)]

            # Histogram with relative frequency
            axes[idx].hist(data_filtered, alpha=0.3, label=f'{segment} (n={len(data)})',
                          bins=30, color=colors[segment], density=True,
                          edgecolor='black', linewidth=0.5)

            # KDE overlay (on filtered data)
            if len(data_filtered) > 1:
                data_filtered.plot(kind='kde', ax=axes[idx], color=colors[segment],
                                  linewidth=2.5, alpha=0.8)

            # Mean line (full data mean)
            mean_val = data.mean()
            if q01 <= mean_val <= q99:  # Only show if within range
                axes[idx].axvline(mean_val, color=colors[segment], linestyle='--',
                                linewidth=2, alpha=0.9)
                axes[idx].text(mean_val, axes[idx].get_ylim()[1]*0.95,
                              f'{segment}\n={mean_val:.2f}',
                              ha='center', fontsize=9, fontweight='bold',
                              bbox=dict(boxstyle='round', facecolor=colors[segment], alpha=0.3))

    # Set x-axis limits to 1st-99th percentile range
    axes[idx].set_xlim(q01, q99)

    axes[idx].set_title(f'{feature}\n(1st-99th percentile range)', fontsize=13, fontweight='bold')
    axes[idx].set_xlabel('Value (non-scaled)', fontsize=11)
    axes[idx].set_ylabel('Density', fontsize=11)
    axes[idx].legend(fontsize=9, loc='best')
    axes[idx].grid(True, alpha=0.3)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.suptitle('Segment Profiles After Reallocation - KDE Distribution Analysis',
             y=1.00, fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
plt.show()

4.2 Modelling conclusion

After ensamble model development and reallocation pipeline, the predicted group still follow the clear economic logic. This ensamble framework can be used for the groups prediction.

Limitations and red flags

The overall cluster separation may still not be sufficient. We can see the SD group to have significant univariate distribution portion above the KVI group for features total_online_views and competitive pressure. It shows that prior to the redistribution, major part of now SD group was classified as KVI.

Productionization

The whole modelling process (without the hyperoptimization) is converted into the production pipeline, where train.py and predict.py, with which the prediction.csv is created. You may find the whole pipeline in the same folder as this notebook. For more details about the production pipeline read the project attached README.txt file.
